When I was trying to figure out why [GROOVY-7922](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-7922) occured, I found that it was because of a mistake in fixing [GROOVY-6970](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-6970). In that solution, the developer was letting an interface's super interfaces (at same level) have different "distances" to it.

For example,

```
interface A{ void foo(); }
interface B{ void foo(); }
interface C extends A, B{ void foo(); }
```

When in static compilation, a specific version of method is chosen by comparing "distance". In this case, the distance of A and B to C is apparently equal, which will result in GROOVY-6970. In [`org.codehaus.groovy.transform.stc.StaticTypeCheckingSupport`](https://github.com/apache/groovy/blob/master/src/main/org/codehaus/groovy/transform/stc/StaticTypeCheckingSupport.java), line 890, we can find that the original solution was that let A and B have different "distance" by adding an additional `i`. I think the solution to GROOVY-6970 is not correct because it will result in GROOVY-7922, so I reverted it and re-fixed GROOVY-6970.

However, I think the distance strategy is imperfect, an implementation of [JLS](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-15.html#jls-15.12.2.5) is necessary.

I'm +1 for this change. But I am keen that we don't forget about the inconsistencies highlighted in the discussion (mailing list and Jira issue).

```
import groovy.transform.*

class Foo {
    private static final int val = 2
    private static final Integer val2 = 3
    int a(int a) { 0 }
    int a(Integer a) { 1 }

    @CompileStatic
    def csMethod() {
        assert a(val) == 0
        assert a(val2) == 1
        def x = a(val)
        assert x == 0
        x = a(val2)
        assert x == 1
    }

    def dynMethod() {
        assert a(val) == 1
        assert a(val2) == 1
        def x = a(val)
        assert x == 0
        x = a(val2)
        assert x == 1
    }
}

new Foo().csMethod()
new Foo().dynMethod()
```

We should either list the differences as bugs or "features" and, if a feature, have some doco somewhere that recommends that if both primitive and wrapper versions of a method are available that they produce the same result so that @CS or primopts won't change the result. (I haven't attempted to document the indy behavior above - but we also need to do this - at least if there are any discrepancies).

I am probably -1 on this proposal assuming that #371 is merged.
It seems to cover all the cases fairly well:

```
import groovy.json.*

def Closure closureWithNullValues = {
  optionalValue null
  constantValue 37
}

def json1 = new JsonBuilder(closureWithNullValues)
assert json1.toString() == '{"optionalValue":null,"constantValue":37}'

def options = JsonOutput.options().excludeNulls()
def json2 = new JsonBuilder(closureWithNullValues, options)
assert json2.toString() == '{"constantValue":37}'

def generator = JsonOutput.options().excludeNulls().createGenerator()
assert generator.toJson(json1.content) == '{"constantValue":37}'

def Expando expandoWithNullValues = new Expando(optionalValue: null, constantValue: 37)
assert generator.toJson(expandoWithNullValues) == '{"constantValue":37}'

TreeMap<String, Integer> mapWithNullValues = [constantValue:37,optionalValue:null]
assert generator.toJson(mapWithNullValues) == '{"constantValue":37}'
```

Perhaps not as cleanly as with a single boolean flag, but in a more general way.

